ing from people with lived experiences -- tEthics in community research: reflections from ethnographic research with First Nations people in the US -- tAvoiding ‘best’ being the enemy of ‘good’: using peer interviewer methods for community research in place-based settings in Australia -- tManaging the research process -- tMental health service users and carers as researchers: reflections on a qualitative study of citizens’ experiences of compulsory mental health laws in Northern Ireland -- tCommunity organisation and community research: women’s struggle for food security in India -- tCommunity researchers in an adolescent risk reduction intervention in Botswana: challenges and opportunities -- tRecruitment and capacity-building challenges in participatory research involving young people in Northern Ireland -- tTranslating lives: cross-language community research with Polish migrants in the UK -- tMentoring refugee community researchers in the UK: an empowerment tool? -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book bridges a major gap in knowledge by considering, through a range of reflexive chapters from different disciplinary backgrounds, both theoretical and practical issues relating to community research methodologies. The international contributors consider a number of key epistemological, ontological and methodological questions. They explore what community peer research means in a range of settings, for a range of people, for the quality of data and subsequent findings, and for the production of rigorous social research. The collection will also stimulate thinking about how methodological advancement can be made in the field. It is the first book of its kind to combine practical and methodological reflections with clearly presented recommendations about how the approach can be used. Presenting the latest thinking in the field and providing summaries, case studies and review questions, 'Community research for participation' will be invaluable to students, researchers, academics and practitioners who aim to place community members at the centre of their research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aCommunity developmentxResearch. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Methodology.2bisacsh1 aAddy, Tony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAndharia, Janki, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAtfield, Gaby, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBell, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlakey, Heather, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrahmbhatt, Kavita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrophy, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuckley, Liam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurns, Stephanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell, Jim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCartland, Jenifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChilisa, Bagele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChilisa, Rapelang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCocks, Nadine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaly, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavidson, Gavin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodson, Lisa, econtributor.4